        <span class="mx-2">/</span>
        <a href="/industries/packaging-line-conveyors/case/" class="hover:text-white/70">Case Packing</a>
        <span class="mx-2">/</span>
        <span class="text-white/70">Robotic</span>
      </nav>
      <div class="max-w-3xl">
        <div class="section-label text-accent-bright/80 mb-6">Case Packing</div>
        <h1 class="font-display text-5xl sm:text-6xl lg:text-7xl font-800 text-white tracking-wide uppercase leading-[0.95] mb-8">
          Robotic <span class="text-accent-bright">Case Packing</span>
        </h1>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <article>
    <section class="py-12 bg-surface-dim" aria-labelledby="aio-heading">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
        <p id="aio-heading" class="text-lg text-ink leading-relaxed">
          Robotic case packing uses delta (spider), articulated arm, or gantry robots to pick products from a conveyor and place them into corrugated cases. Vision systems locate products on the infeed belt, vacuum or mechanical grippers pick single or multiple items, and programmed motion paths place product into precise case patterns. Robotic case packers from FANUC, ABB, KUKA, Yaskawa, and packaging OEMs like Brenton (ProMach), BluePrint Automation (BPA), and JLS Automation handle 15 to 120+ picks per minute with recipe-based changeover for multiple product sizes and case configurations.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ═══ ROBOT TYPES ═══ -->
    <section class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="types-heading">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
        <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Robot Types</div>
        <h2 id="types-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide uppercase mb-8">
          Delta, Articulated & <span class="text-accent">Gantry Robots</span>
        </h2>
        <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-5">
          <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink mt-4 mb-4">Delta (Spider) Robots</h3>
          <p>
            Delta robots use three or four parallel-link arms attached to a fixed overhead frame. The lightweight arm structure enables high-speed pick-and-place — 60 to 120+ picks per minute per robot. Delta robots pick from a moving conveyor belt using vision-guided tracking. The robot controller receives product position data from an upstream camera, calculates the pick trajectory, and synchronizes with the belt encoder to pick product in motion.
          </p>
          <p>
            Delta robots suit lightweight products (under 2-5 lb depending on model): flow-wrapped snacks, pouches, bags, small cartons, and individual <a href="/industries/food-conveyors/bakery/cookie-cracker/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">cookie packages</a>. FANUC M-1iA/M-3iA, ABB FlexPicker IRB 360, and Yaskawa MPP3 are common delta robot models in packaging. <!-- VERIFY: Current delta robot model numbers -->
          </p>

          <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink mt-10 mb-4">Articulated Arm Robots</h3>
          <p>
            Articulated arm (6-axis) robots provide greater reach, payload, and flexibility than delta robots. Six joints allow the robot to approach the product from any angle, rotate it during placement, and reach into deep cases. Payload ranges from 5 to 250+ kg depending on model. Speeds are lower than delta — typically 15-40 picks per minute — because the heavier arm structure limits acceleration.
          </p>
          <p>
            Articulated arms suit heavier products (cases, trays, multipacks weighing 5-50+ lb), mixed-case packing (multiple SKUs into one case), and applications requiring product reorientation during placement. FANUC M-10/M-20, ABB IRB 2600, and KUKA KR AGILUS are widely used for case packing. These robots also handle palletizing — a single robot can pack cases and palletize them in lower-volume applications.
          </p>

          <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink mt-10 mb-4">Gantry (Cartesian) Robots</h3>
          <p>
            Gantry robots use linear axes (X, Y, Z) mounted on an overhead frame. The pick head travels along rails above the product conveyor and case conveyor. Gantry systems handle very heavy loads (100+ lb) and provide a large work envelope. They pick entire product layers (a complete row or partial case pattern) in a single motion, then place the layer into the case.
          </p>
          <p>
            Gantry packers suit high-volume lines packing heavy products — beverage multipacks, canned goods trays, and bulk-packaged industrial products. Speeds are moderate (10-25 CPM) but each cycle places multiple products. Schneider Packaging (Pactiv Evergreen) and Pearson Packaging supply gantry-style case packers. <!-- VERIFY: Schneider Packaging current ownership/branding -->
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ═══ COMPARISON TABLE ═══ -->
    <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim" aria-labelledby="compare-heading">
      <div class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
        <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Comparison</div>
