            <thead>
              <tr class="border-b-2 border-ink">
                <th class="font-display text-base font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink py-4 pr-4">Robot Type</th>
                <th class="font-display text-base font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink py-4 pr-4">Speed (Picks/Min)</th>
                <th class="font-display text-base font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink py-4 pr-4">Payload</th>
                <th class="font-display text-base font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink py-4 pr-4">Best For</th>
                <th class="font-display text-base font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink py-4">Relative Cost</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody class="text-base text-ink-muted">
              <tr class="border-b border-border">
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-semibold text-ink">Delta (spider)</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">60-120+</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">0.5-5 lb</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4">Light products, high speed, food</td>
                <td class="py-4 font-mono text-sm">$$$</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="border-b border-border">
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-semibold text-ink">Articulated arm</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">15-40</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">5-250+ lb</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4">Heavy products, mixed case, flexibility</td>
                <td class="py-4 font-mono text-sm">$$$-$$$$</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-semibold text-ink">Gantry (Cartesian)</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">10-25 (layer picks)</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">50-300+ lb</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4">Heavy, high-volume, full-layer</td>
                <td class="py-4 font-mono text-sm">$$$$</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ═══ VISION SYSTEMS ═══ -->
    <section class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="vision-heading">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
        <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Vision Integration</div>
        <h2 id="vision-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide uppercase mb-8">
          Vision Systems & <span class="text-accent">Conveyor Tracking</span>
        </h2>
        <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-5">
          <p>
            Vision-guided robotic case packing uses cameras above the product infeed conveyor to locate, identify, and determine the orientation of each product. The vision system sends product coordinates and rotation angle to the robot controller, which calculates a pick trajectory synchronized to the belt's motion via encoder feedback.
          </p>
          <p>
            The product infeed conveyor for vision-guided picking requires specific design features:
          </p>
          <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-3 ml-2">
            <li><strong class="text-ink">Consistent belt color:</strong> White or light-colored belts provide contrast against most products. Dark belts suit light-colored products.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-ink">Controlled lighting:</strong> Overhead LED bar lights or diffuse dome lights eliminate shadows and reflections. The conveyor section under the camera often has a light enclosure to block ambient light variation.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-ink">Encoder feedback:</strong> A belt-mounted encoder or motor encoder provides precise belt position to the robot controller. Encoder resolution of 0.1mm or better ensures accurate product tracking at speed.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-ink">Single-layer product:</strong> Products must arrive in a single layer, not stacked. A <a href="/conveyor-functions/product-handling/spreader/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">spreader conveyor</a> or singulation conveyor upstream ensures single-layer presentation.</li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            Cognex, Keyence, and SICK supply vision systems for robotic packaging applications. FANUC's iRVision and ABB's integrated vision are robot-native vision solutions that simplify integration.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ═══ GRIPPER DESIGN ═══ -->
    <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim" aria-labelledby="gripper-heading">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
        <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">End-of-Arm Tooling</div>
        <h2 id="gripper-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide uppercase mb-8">
          Gripper <span class="text-accent">Design</span>
        </h2>
        <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-5">
          <p>
            The gripper (end-of-arm tool, EOAT) determines what products the robot can pick and how gently it handles them. Gripper design is the most application-specific element of a robotic case packing system. Common gripper types:
          </p>
          <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-3 ml-2">
            <li><strong class="text-ink">Vacuum grippers:</strong> Suction cups pick products with flat or slightly curved surfaces — bags, pouches, cartons, flow-wrapped packages. Single or multi-cup configurations pick one or multiple products per cycle. Foam or bellows cups conform to irregular surfaces. Vacuum is generated by venturi (compressed air) or electric vacuum pump.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-ink">Mechanical grippers:</strong> Fingers or jaws clamp around the product. Suited for rigid items (bottles, cans, tubes) that vacuum cups cannot grip reliably. Servo-controlled fingers adjust grip force for different product sizes.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-ink">Fork/shovel grippers:</strong> Thin forks slide under the product (from the belt surface) and lift. Used for fragile products that cannot tolerate top-surface pressure — decorated <a href="/industries/food-conveyors/bakery/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">bakery products</a>, open containers, and delicate trays.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-ink">Multi-pick grippers:</strong> Gripper with multiple independent pick heads picks 2-8 products per cycle. Reduces required robot speed — a 4-pick gripper at 30 cycles/minute achieves 120 picks/minute. Common with delta robots on high-speed lines.</li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            Gripper changeover for different products takes 5-30 minutes for a manual tool change or 15-30 seconds with an automatic tool changer (ATC). Automatic tool changers from Schunk, ATI, and Applied Robotics enable tool-free recipe changes. The robot stores multiple grippers on a rack and swaps automatically when the operator selects a new product recipe.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ═══ CONVEYOR REQUIREMENTS ═══ -->
    <section class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="conveyor-heading">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
        <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Conveyor Integration</div>
        <h2 id="conveyor-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide uppercase mb-8">
          Conveyor Requirements for <span class="text-accent">Robotic Packing</span>
        </h2>
        <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-5">
          <p>
            A robotic case packing cell requires three conveyor subsystems working in coordination:
          </p>
          <ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-4 ml-2">
            <li><strong class="text-ink">Product infeed conveyor:</strong> Delivers products to the robot pick zone. Belt conveyor running at constant speed (20-100 FPM typical). Servo-controlled belt with encoder feedback for vision tracking. Width sized for single-file or multi-lane product presentation. <a href="/conveyor-functions/infeed-outfeed/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Infeed system</a> upstream meters product spacing.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-ink">Case conveyor:</strong> Positions empty cases under the robot place zone. <a href="/conveyor-functions/indexing-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Indexing conveyor</a> for stop-and-go placement, or continuous conveyor with tracking for place-on-the-fly operation. Case erector feeds empty cases from upstream.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-ink">Case discharge conveyor:</strong> Transports loaded cases from the robot cell to case sealing and palletizing. Roller or belt conveyor with <a href="/conveyor-types/accumulation-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">accumulation</a> to buffer cases when the sealer stops.</li>
          </ol>
          <p>
            All three conveyors communicate through the cell PLC or robot controller. The product infeed encoder feeds the vision tracking system. The case conveyor indexes in sync with the robot cycle. The discharge conveyor receives a "case full" signal and advances the loaded case. For more on controls integration, see the <a href="/resources/automated-conveyor-systems/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">automated conveyor systems guide</a>.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ═══ SAFETY ═══ -->
    <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim" aria-labelledby="safety-heading">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
        <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Safety</div>
        <h2 id="safety-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide uppercase mb-8">
          Safety Guarding & <span class="text-accent">Conveyor Access</span>
        </h2>
        <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-5">
          <p>
            Robotic case packing cells require safety guarding per ANSI/RIA 15.06 and OSHA standards. The robot work envelope must be enclosed by safety fencing, light curtains, or area scanners. Conveyor entry and exit points through the safety perimeter use safety-rated muting sensors that allow product to pass while detecting human intrusion.
          </p>
          <p>
            Collaborative robots (cobots) from Universal Robots, FANUC (CRX series), and ABB (GoFa/SWIFTI) operate without full safety fencing in some case packing applications. Cobots limit speed and force to safe levels when humans are nearby. However, cobot speed limitations (typically 250mm/s or less in collaborative mode) reduce throughput compared to industrial robots. Cobots suit lower-volume, high-mix applications where operators frequently interact with the cell. <!-- VERIFY: Current cobot speed limits in collaborative mode per ISO/TS 15066 -->
          </p>
          <p>
            For budgeting, robotic case packing cells cost $$$-$$$$ depending on robot type, vision system, gripper complexity, and conveyor requirements. See the <a href="/resources/conveyor-cost-guide/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">conveyor cost guide</a> for cost factors.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>
  </article>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="faq-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <h2 id="faq-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide uppercase mb-10">
        Frequently Asked <span class="text-accent">Questions</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="space-y-4">
        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8" open>
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            What is robotic case packing?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" /></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-3">
            <p>Robotic case packing uses industrial robots to pick products from a conveyor and place them into cases. Delta robots handle lightweight products at high speed; articulated arms handle heavier products with greater flexibility. Vision systems guide picking from moving belts.</p>
          </div>
        </details>
        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8">
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            Delta vs. articulated arm for case packing?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" /></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-3">
            <p>Delta: 60-120+ picks/min, under 5 lb payload, ideal for food packaging. Articulated arm: 15-40 picks/min, 5-250+ lb payload, suits heavy products and mixed-case applications. See also: <a href="/industries/packaging-line-conveyors/case/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">case packing overview</a>.</p>
          </div>
        </details>
        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8">
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            How fast can robotic case packers run?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" /></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-3">
            <p>Single delta robot: 60-120+ picks/min. Single articulated arm: 15-40 picks/min. Multi-robot cells multiply throughput. A 2-robot delta cell typically packs 20-40 cases/min depending on products per case.</p>
          </div>
        </details>
        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8">
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            What conveyors does robotic case packing need?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" /></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-3">
            <p>Three conveyors: product infeed (belt with encoder for vision tracking), case conveyor (<a href="/conveyor-functions/indexing-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">indexing</a> or continuous for case positioning), and case discharge (roller or belt to sealing/palletizing). All coordinate through the cell PLC.</p>
          </div>
        </details>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

</BaseLayout>
